ching court decisions in the nation in school finance and education reform, Framing Equal Opportunity follows lawyers and activists in New Jersey and Kentucky as they negotiate the complicated political terrain of educational change in their respective states. Unlike other books on law and reform, this work emphasizes the importance of legal translation-the process through which reformers transform their visions and goals into plausible legal claims. As it reveals, the kinds of arguments lawyers choose to make matter not only to their success in the courtroom, but also to the nature of the political fights they face in the community at large.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEducationxFinancexLaw and legislationxKentucky. 0aEducationxFinancexLaw and legislationxNew Jersey. 0aEducationxFinancexLaw and legislationzKentucky. 0aEducationxFinancexLaw and legislationzNew Jersey. 0aEducational equalizationxLaw and legislationxKentuckyxKentuckyxNew JerseyxElectronic books. 0aEducational equalizationxLaw and legislationxNew Jersey. 0aEducational equalizationxLaw and legislationzKentucky. 0aEducational equalizationxLaw and legislationzNew Jersey. 7aLAW / Educational Law & Legislation.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477297640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804772976423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804772976.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles